This paper deals with the complexity of languages and the power of different computational models, which suggests that it belongs to the category of computational complexity (cs.CC). The paper also involves information theory (cs.IT) in its analysis of the error probabilities of the prover games. The use of probabilistic algorithms and the study of the complexity of decision problems suggest that it could also belong to the categories of data structures (cs.DS) and machine learning (cs.LG). Finally, the paper's exploration of the relationship between complexity classes suggests that it could also belong to the category of artificial intelligence (cs.AI).
